The veracity of extracts from different parts of plants (including roots, stems, leaves, and fruits) as anti-hyperglycaemic agents has been established (
 Hussein, 2008; 
 Singab et al., 2014; 
 Emordi et al., 2018). For example, banana root and shoot extracts, plantain root and stem extracts have been adjudged by folklore to possess medicinal properties such as antidiabetic and antilipidemic potentials (
 Omobuwajo et al., 2011; 
 Kalita et al., 2016). In addition, parts (e.g. roots, stems, leaves, and fruits) of 
 Musa spp. (especially bananas) have been shown to have health promoting properties (
 Ibegbu et al., 2012; 
 Lakshmi et al., 2014; 
 Nguyen et al., 2017).
